Type `quit` to exit this chatbot.
APR stands for Annual Percentage Rate. It's a measure used to compare the cost of borrowing money across different loans or credit products. The APR includes not only the interest rate but also any additional fees and costs associated with the loan, providing a more comprehensive view of the total cost of borrowing.

For example, if you're looking at two loans with the same interest rate, but one has higher origination fees than the other, the APR will help you understand which loan is actually cheaper in the long run. The APR can be used to compare different types of loans such as mortgages, car loans, personal loans, and credit cards.

It's important to note that while APR provides a good comparison tool for borrowing costs, it doesn't account for potential future changes in interest rates or fees. Therefore, it should be one of several factors considered when choosing a loan product.



